Note: ================================================================
Note: Makefile Translation Emitter
Note: ================================================================
Note: High-level orchestration for Makefile bidirectional translation.
Note: Coordinates lexer, parser, translator, and backend to provide:
Note:   - Makefile source → HIR translation
Note:   - HIR → Makefile source generation
Note:   - Round-trip translation (Makefile → HIR → Makefile)
Note:   - Diagnostic reporting and error handling
Note:   - Integration with Translation universal translation system
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/makefile/makefile_lexer.runa" as MakefileLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/makefile/makefile_parser.runa" as MakefileParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/makefile/makefile_to_hir.runa" as MakefileToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/makefile/hir_to_makefile.runa" as HIRToMakefile
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrimitive
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/io/file_io.runa" as FileIO
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore

Note: ================================================================
Note: Emitter State
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The emitter is the orchestrator across four pipeline stages (lexer, parser, translator, backend); holding their pointers lets a caller inspect any stage's state after the pipeline runs, which is essential for diagnostic reporting and incremental editing. error_list and warning_list aggregate diagnostics across all stages so the consumer sees a single unified view rather than four separate queries.
@End Reasoning
Type called "MakefileEmitter":
    source_file_path as String  Note: Path to source Makefile
    error_list as Integer  Note: Pointer to list of errors across all stages
    warning_list as Integer  Note: Pointer to list of warnings across all stages
    lexer_ptr as Integer  Note: Pointer to lexer state
    parser_ptr as Integer  Note: Pointer to parser state
    translator_ptr as Integer  Note: Pointer to translator state
    backend_ptr as Integer  Note: Pointer to backend state
    ast_root as Integer  Note: Pointer to AST root node
    hir_root as Integer  Note: Pointer to HIR root node
End Type

Note: ================================================================
Note: Diagnostic Types
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
A diagnostic record carries everything the formatter needs: severity (info/warning/error), message text, file location, and originating pipeline stage. Bundling stage with the diagnostic lets consumers filter by stage ("show only translator warnings") without re-walking the source emitter.
@End Reasoning
Type called "Diagnostic":
    severity as Integer  Note: 0 = info, 1 = warning, 2 = error
    message as String
    file_path as String
    line_number as Integer
    column_number as Integer
    stage as String  Note: "lexer", "parser", "translator", "backend"
End Type

Note: ================================================================
Note: Emitter Initialization
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The emitter is allocated as a 72-byte struct (9 slots) so all stage pointers and diagnostic lists live in one heap allocation; this keeps cache locality high during pipeline execution. Stage pointers (lexer/parser/translator/backend) are left null and only created on demand because some entry points (validate_makefile) need only the early stages.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_emitter" that takes nothing returns Integer:
    Let emitter_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 72

    Note: Initialize source file path
    proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 0, ""

    Note: Initialize diagnostic lists
    Let error_list be proc list_create from ListCore
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 8, error_list

    Let warning_list be proc list_create from ListCore
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 16, warning_list

    Note: Initialize stage pointers (created on demand)
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 24, 0  Note: lexer_ptr
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 32, 0  Note: parser_ptr
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 40, 0  Note: translator_ptr
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 48, 0  Note: backend_ptr

    Note: Initialize AST and HIR roots
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 56, 0  Note: ast_root
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 64, 0  Note: hir_root

    Return emitter_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Makefile → AST (Lexing and Parsing)
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lexing and parsing are coupled into one entry point because makefile tokens are not consumable independently of the parser's state (TAB tokens are only meaningful in recipe context). We check lexer errors before invoking the parser so the parser is never fed an inconsistent token stream; the same gate appears after parsing so a partial AST is never written to the emitter.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
makefile_source is untrusted user input; lexer and parser both append to their own diagnostic lists rather than aborting, so a malformed makefile produces a clean error report instead of a crash.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "parse_makefile" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer, makefile_source as String returns Integer:
    Note: Create and run lexer
    Let lexer_ptr be proc create_lexer from MakefileLexer with makefile_source
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 24, lexer_ptr

    Let tokens_list be proc tokenize from MakefileLexer with lexer_ptr

    Note: Collect lexer errors
    Let lexer_errors be proc get_lexer_errors with lexer_ptr
    proc merge_diagnostics with emitter_ptr, lexer_errors, "lexer", 2  Note: 2 = error severity

    Note: Check for lexer errors
    Let lexer_error_count be proc list_length from ListCore with lexer_errors
    If lexer_error_count is greater than 0:
        Return 0  Note: Lexing failed
    End If

    Note: Create and run parser
    Let parser_ptr be proc create_parser from MakefileParser with tokens_list
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 32, parser_ptr

    Let ast_root be proc parse_makefile from MakefileParser with parser_ptr

    Note: Collect parser errors
    Let parser_errors be proc get_parser_errors with parser_ptr
    proc merge_diagnostics with emitter_ptr, parser_errors, "parser", 2

    Note: Check for parser errors
    Let parser_error_count be proc list_length from ListCore with parser_errors
    If parser_error_count is greater than 0:
        Return 0  Note: Parsing failed
    End If

    Note: Store AST root
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 56, ast_root

    Return 1  Note: Success
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: AST → HIR Translation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
AST-to-HIR translation is a separate stage because some callers want the AST only (linting, formatting); requiring a prior parse_makefile keeps each stage focused on a single concern. The null-AST guard emits an explicit diagnostic so misuse (calling translate before parse) shows up as a translator-stage error instead of a silent failure.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_to_hir" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get AST root
    Let ast_root be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 56

    If ast_root is equal to 0:
        proc add_diagnostic with emitter_ptr, 2, "No AST available for translation", "", 0, 0, "translator"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create translator
    Let translator_ptr be proc create_translator from MakefileToHIR
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 40, translator_ptr

    Note: Translate AST to HIR
    Let hir_root be proc translate_makefile from MakefileToHIR with translator_ptr, ast_root

    Note: Collect translator errors and warnings
    Let translator_errors be proc get_translator_errors with translator_ptr
    proc merge_diagnostics with emitter_ptr, translator_errors, "translator", 2

    Let translator_warnings be proc get_translator_warnings with translator_ptr
    proc merge_diagnostics with emitter_ptr, translator_warnings, "translator", 1  Note: 1 = warning

    Note: Check for errors
    Let translator_error_count be proc list_length from ListCore with translator_errors
    If translator_error_count is greater than 0:
        Return 0  Note: Translation failed
    End If

    If hir_root is equal to 0:
        proc add_diagnostic with emitter_ptr, 2, "Translation produced null HIR", "", 0, 0, "translator"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Store HIR root
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 64, hir_root

    Return 1  Note: Success
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: HIR → Makefile Generation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
HIR-to-Makefile generation is the inverse of translate_to_hir; we return the empty string on failure rather than a sentinel value because the empty makefile is unambiguously invalid (a real makefile always has at least one rule or directive). The backend's own error_list captures the specific failure cause.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_makefile" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer returns String:
    Note: Get HIR root
    Let hir_root be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 64

    If hir_root is equal to 0:
        proc add_diagnostic with emitter_ptr, 2, "No HIR available for code generation", "", 0, 0, "backend"
        Return ""
    End If

    Note: Create backend
    Let backend_ptr be proc create_backend from HIRToMakefile
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 48, backend_ptr

    Note: Generate Makefile source
    Let makefile_source be proc translate from HIRToMakefile with hir_root

    Note: Collect backend errors
    Let backend_errors be proc get_backend_errors with backend_ptr
    proc merge_diagnostics with emitter_ptr, backend_errors, "backend", 2

    Note: Check for errors
    Let backend_error_count be proc list_length from ListCore with backend_errors
    If backend_error_count is greater than 0:
        Return ""  Note: Generation failed
    End If

    If proc string_length from StringCore with makefile_source is equal to 0:
        proc add_diagnostic with emitter_ptr, 2, "Backend produced empty output", "", 0, 0, "backend"
        Return ""
    End If

    Return makefile_source
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: High-Level Translation Operations
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The "with_emitter" variant exists so callers managing a long-lived emitter (e.g., an LSP that wants persistent diagnostic history) can run the pipeline without paying the create/teardown cost per call. Short-circuit returns on each stage failure ensure the emitter's state remains consistent with what was actually accomplished.
@End Reasoning
Process called "makefile_to_hir_with_emitter" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer, makefile_source as String returns Integer:
    Note: Parse Makefile source
    Let parse_success be proc parse_makefile with emitter_ptr, makefile_source

    If parse_success is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Parsing failed
    End If

    Note: Translate to HIR
    Let translate_success be proc translate_to_hir with emitter_ptr

    If translate_success is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Translation failed
    End If

    Note: Return HIR root
    Let hir_root be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 64
    Return hir_root
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR-to-Makefile lives in the emitter so the backend diagnostics aggregate with any prior stages' diagnostics; writing hir_root into the emitter slot before calling generate_makefile gives the backend a stable handle and keeps the emitter's get_hir_root accessor consistent with what was actually emitted.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_to_makefile_with_emitter" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer, hir_root as Integer returns String:
    Note: Store HIR root in emitter
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 64, hir_root

    Note: Generate Makefile source
    Let makefile_source be proc generate_makefile with emitter_ptr

    Return makefile_source
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Dispatcher Entry Points - Single-Arg Wrappers
Note: ================================================================
Note: The central dispatcher in translation.runa calls the orchestrator by
Note: the canonical single-arg shape. These wrappers create a fresh emitter,
Note: run the pipeline, and return the result so the dispatcher does not
Note: need to manage emitter lifecycles.

@Reasoning:
The single-arg shape is what the central translation dispatcher in translation.runa calls; keeping it as a thin wrapper around create_emitter + with_emitter avoids duplicating pipeline logic while letting callers who don't need emitter lifecycle management ignore it entirely.
@End Reasoning
Process called "makefile_to_hir" that takes makefile_source as String returns Integer:
    Let emitter_ptr be proc create_emitter
    Return proc makefile_to_hir_with_emitter with emitter_ptr, makefile_source
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-arg HIR-to-Makefile entry point mirrors makefile_to_hir; the dispatcher contract is symmetric so both directions of translation are interchangeable from the caller's perspective.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_to_makefile" that takes hir_root as Integer returns String:
    Let emitter_ptr be proc create_emitter
    Return proc hir_to_makefile_with_emitter with emitter_ptr, hir_root
End Process

@Reasoning:
Round-trip translation is the standard golden-output test mechanism: parse, translate to HIR, then re-emit and diff against the original (modulo formatting). It's also useful as a normalizer — the output is what the canonical formatter would produce for the same semantic content. Both stages share the same emitter so diagnostics from either direction accumulate.
@End Reasoning
Process called "round_trip_translate" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer, makefile_source as String returns String:
    Note: Parse and translate to HIR
    Let hir_root be proc makefile_to_hir_with_emitter with emitter_ptr, makefile_source

    If hir_root is equal to 0:
        Return ""  Note: Makefile → HIR failed
    End If

    Note: Translate back to Makefile
    Let regenerated_source be proc generate_makefile with emitter_ptr

    Return regenerated_source
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Diagnostic Management
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The seven-arg shape collects every diagnostic field at the call site so the resulting record is fully populated; downstream consumers (format_diagnostic, IDE) can render exactly one consistent format. Severity >= 2 routes to error_list, < 2 to warning_list, so a future "info" severity (0) lands in warning_list which is intentional because the IDE shows warnings and infos with the same UI treatment.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_diagnostic" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer, severity as Integer, message as String, file_path as String, line as Integer, column as Integer, stage as String returns Integer:
    Let diag_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 48

    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with diag_ptr, 0, severity
    proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with diag_ptr, 8, message
    proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with diag_ptr, 16, file_path
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with diag_ptr, 24, line
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with diag_ptr, 32, column
    proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with diag_ptr, 40, stage

    If severity is greater than or equal to 2:
        Note: Error
        Let error_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 8
        proc list_append from ListCore with error_list, diag_ptr
    Otherwise:
        Note: Warning or info
        Let warning_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 16
        proc list_append from ListCore with warning_list, diag_ptr
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Stage-specific diagnostic lists (lexer, parser, translator, backend) use their own field layouts so we deliberately re-extract message/line/column at known offsets and reformat them through add_diagnostic; this normalizes everything to the emitter's diagnostic format and tags each record with the originating stage for downstream filtering.
@End Reasoning
Process called "merge_diagnostics" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer, diag_list as Integer, stage as String, severity as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with diag_list
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let stage_diag_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with diag_list, index

        Note: Extract fields from stage diagnostic (format may vary by stage)
        Let message be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with stage_diag_ptr, 0
        Let line be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with stage_diag_ptr, 8
        Let column be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with stage_diag_ptr, 16

        Note: Add to emitter diagnostics with standardized format
        Let file_path be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 0
        proc add_diagnostic with emitter_ptr, severity, message, file_path, line, column, stage

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Error count is exposed as an accessor so the underlying representation (list, set, or deduped buffer) can change without breaking consumers; the same applies to warnings. Two separate accessors avoid forcing callers to split a single combined list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_error_count" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let error_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 8
    Return proc list_length from ListCore with error_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Warning count mirrors error count; warnings are tracked separately because IDE and CLI surfaces treat them differently (warnings are suppressible, errors are not).
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_warning_count" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let warning_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 16
    Return proc list_length from ListCore with warning_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
The combined diagnostic list is built fresh each call rather than cached so consumers receive a coherent snapshot; errors come first to match the convention that severity descending is the most useful display order. The function allocates a new list and shares pointers to the underlying diagnostic records (no deep copy) because diagnostics are immutable after add_diagnostic.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_diagnostics" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let all_diagnostics be proc list_create from ListCore

    Note: Add all errors first
    Let error_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 8
    Let error_count be proc list_length from ListCore with error_list
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than error_count:
        Let error_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with error_list, index
        proc list_append from ListCore with all_diagnostics, error_ptr
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add all warnings
    Let warning_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 16
    Let warning_count be proc list_length from ListCore with warning_list
    Set index to 0

    While index is less than warning_count:
        Let warning_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with warning_list, index
        proc list_append from ListCore with all_diagnostics, warning_ptr
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return all_diagnostics
End Process

@Reasoning:
The diagnostic format follows the conventional "path:line:col: severity [stage]: message" layout used by GCC/Clang/MSVC so IDEs and editors can parse it with their standard regexes. The leading location is omitted when file_path is empty so synthetic diagnostics (e.g., "no AST available") don't render with a misleading "0:0" prefix.
@End Reasoning
Process called "format_diagnostic" that takes diag_ptr as Integer returns String:
    Let severity be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with diag_ptr, 0
    Let message be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with diag_ptr, 8
    Let file_path be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with diag_ptr, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with diag_ptr, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with diag_ptr, 32
    Let stage be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with diag_ptr, 40

    Note: Build diagnostic string
    Let result be ""

    Note: Add file location if available
    If proc string_length from StringCore with file_path is greater than 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, file_path
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, ":"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, proc integer_to_string from StringPrimitive with line
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, ":"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, proc integer_to_string from StringPrimitive with column
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, ": "
    End If

    Note: Add severity label
    If severity is equal to 2:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, "error"
    Otherwise:
        If severity is equal to 1:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, "warning"
        Otherwise:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, "info"
        End If
    End If

    Note: Add stage
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, " ["
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, stage
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, "]: "

    Note: Add message
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with result, message

    Return result
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Stage-Specific Error Retrieval
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The lexer records at most one error inline in its struct (error_message at
offset 48, has_error flag at offset 56 — see makefile_lexer.create_lexer),
rather than maintaining an error list. merge_diagnostics, however, consumes a
list of diagnostic records whose fields are message at offset 0, line at
offset 8, column at offset 16. This accessor bridges the two contracts: it
returns an empty list when the lexer reported no error, otherwise a one-entry
list holding a diagnostic record built from the lexer's stored message. Line
and column are zero because the lexer's single-error model does not retain the
position of the failure; downstream formatting suppresses a zero location.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_lexer_errors" that takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let error_list be proc list_create from ListCore

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with lexer_ptr, 56
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Let message be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with lexer_ptr, 48
        Let diag_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 24
        proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with diag_ptr, 0, message
        proc memory_set_integer from Memory with diag_ptr, 8, 0  Note: line (lexer keeps no position for its single error)
        proc memory_set_integer from Memory with diag_ptr, 16, 0  Note: column
        proc list_append from ListCore with error_list, diag_ptr
    End If

    Return error_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser, like the lexer, records at most one error inline (error_message
at offset 16, has_error flag at offset 24 — see makefile_parser.create_parser).
This accessor mirrors get_lexer_errors: it materializes the parser's single-
error state as a list of zero or one diagnostic records in the message@0 /
line@8 / column@16 shape that merge_diagnostics expects, keeping the stage
error-collection path uniform across lexer and parser.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_parser_errors" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let error_list be proc list_create from ListCore

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with parser_ptr, 24
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Let message be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with parser_ptr, 16
        Let diag_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 24
        proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with diag_ptr, 0, message
        proc memory_set_integer from Memory with diag_ptr, 8, 0  Note: line
        proc memory_set_integer from Memory with diag_ptr, 16, 0  Note: column
        proc list_append from ListCore with error_list, diag_ptr
    End If

    Return error_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
The translator (makefile_to_hir) stores its error records in a ListCore list
at offset 40 of the translator struct, each record in the message@0 / line@8 /
column@16 shape that merge_diagnostics consumes (see
makefile_to_hir.add_translation_error). MakefileToHIR.get_error_count returns
only a count, so merge_diagnostics — which iterates the list — needs the list
itself. This accessor reads the list pointer directly; the offset is part of
the translator's established field layout.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_translator_errors" that takes translator_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let error_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 40
    Return error_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Translator warnings live in a separate ListCore list at offset 48 (see
makefile_to_hir.add_translation_warning), using the same record shape as
errors. Returning the list (not the count) keeps merge_diagnostics' iteration
contract uniform with get_translator_errors.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_translator_warnings" that takes translator_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let warning_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 48
    Return warning_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
The backend error list lives at offset 32 (backend's smaller struct than lexer/parser); the direct read works because this emitter is the backend's sole owner. Backend errors typically reflect HIR-shape violations that the translator failed to catch.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_backend_errors" that takes backend_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let error_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 32
    Return error_list
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Utility Functions
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The source file path is stored on the emitter so every diagnostic emitted afterwards is automatically stamped with it via merge_diagnostics; callers using read-from-string entry points may legitimately leave the path empty, in which case format_diagnostic suppresses the location prefix.
@End Reasoning
Process called "set_source_file_path" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer, file_path as String returns Integer:
    proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 0, file_path
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The AST accessor returns 0 when parse_makefile has not been called or failed; callers must check for 0 before dereferencing. Direct memory read at offset 56 (the documented ast_root slot).
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_ast_root" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc memory_get_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 56
End Process

@Reasoning:
The HIR accessor parallels get_ast_root with offset 64; returning 0 signals translation has not run or has failed, distinguishing "no HIR yet" from "HIR is empty" (an empty HIR root would still be a valid non-zero pointer).
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_hir_root" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc memory_get_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 64
End Process

@Reasoning:
has_errors is a boolean wrapper around get_error_count so callers expressing "did anything go wrong?" don't need to compare against 0; the return is 1/0 rather than the count so it's directly usable as a condition value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "has_errors" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let error_count be proc get_error_count with emitter_ptr

    If error_count is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Public API - Convenience Functions
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The file-path convenience wrapper bundles read-file + pipeline so command-line tools don't reimplement the file-IO boilerplate. FileIO.read_entire_file returns 0 (a null buffer) on a missing or unreadable file, so we short-circuit on a null buffer before running the pipeline; an existing-but-empty file yields a non-null zero-length buffer that flows through normally and produces an empty (but valid) translation.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
file_path is treated as untrusted; FileIO.read_entire_file is responsible for path validation and bounds the read at FILE_MAX_SIZE. The emitter stores file_path on the source_file_path slot so diagnostics carry the user's original (potentially relative) path string for correct IDE source navigation.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "parse_makefile_file" that takes file_path as String returns Integer:
    Note: Read file content
    Let makefile_source be proc read_entire_file from FileIO with file_path

    If makefile_source is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: File read failed
    End If

    Note: Create emitter and parse
    Let emitter_ptr be proc create_emitter
    proc set_source_file_path with emitter_ptr, file_path

    Let hir_root be proc makefile_to_hir_with_emitter with emitter_ptr, makefile_source

    Return hir_root
End Process

@Reasoning:
The inverse file-IO convenience: HIR -> source -> file in one call. We check for empty generated source before writing because writing an empty file would silently overwrite an existing makefile with nothing; returning 0 forces the caller to investigate the diagnostic stream.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_makefile_file" that takes hir_root as Integer, output_path as String returns Integer:
    Note: Create emitter and generate
    Let emitter_ptr be proc create_emitter

    Let makefile_source be proc hir_to_makefile_with_emitter with emitter_ptr, hir_root

    If proc string_length from StringCore with makefile_source is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Generation failed
    End If

    Note: Write to file
    Let write_success be proc write_entire_file from FileIO with output_path, makefile_source

    Return write_success
End Process

@Reasoning:
File-to-file round-trip wraps round_trip_translate with both file-IO ends; this is the canonical entry point for makefile-format normalization tools. The guards cover a null read buffer (missing/unreadable input) and an empty regeneration result so no output file is written on any stage's failure.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_makefile_file" that takes input_path as String, output_path as String returns Integer:
    Note: Read input file
    Let makefile_source be proc read_entire_file from FileIO with input_path

    If makefile_source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create emitter and perform round-trip
    Let emitter_ptr be proc create_emitter
    proc set_source_file_path with emitter_ptr, input_path

    Let regenerated_source be proc round_trip_translate with emitter_ptr, makefile_source

    If proc string_length from StringCore with regenerated_source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Write output file
    Let write_success be proc write_entire_file from FileIO with output_path, regenerated_source

    Return write_success
End Process

